m at about twenty, traveling the American South and the West Indies selling their books. He had a notably fine bass voice and was much in demand in musical circles."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"Rejected for war, undone by his spine","body":"He enlisted in the 14th Connecticut Regiment in 1862 and was surprised to be rejected for physical disability — a judgment soon justified when a worsening spinal condition forced him to give up farming. He died after long suffering at thirty-eight, having represented Durham in the 1868 Assembly."}],"slug":"john-burwell-newton-1836"},"HD6422":{"id":"HD6422","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"generation_from_thomas":7},"bio":{"display_name":"John Newton","first_name":"John","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[]},"birth":{"year":1798,"date_precision":"exact","month":8,"day":5},"death":{"year":1872,"date_precision":"exact","month":2,"day":29},"parents":{"father_id":"HD0164","mother_id":"I01776"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I01789","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1838,"date_month":2,"date_day":21,"children_ids":["HD6460"]}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"character","header":"He praised five brothers who never quarreled","body":"A merchant in the South, Durham, and Middletown who ended his days in Jersey City, John Newton wrote admiringly of his father’s generation — the five brothers Abiathar, Burwell, Abner, Roger, and Isaac — saying he never knew so upright a band of brothers, among whom no word of censure ever passed."}],"slug":"john-newton-1798"},"I01789":{"id":"I01789","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"generation_from_thomas":null},"bio":{"display_name":"Rosina Milford Hearn Newton","first_name":"Rosina Milford","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[],"maiden_name":"Hearn"},"birth":{"year":1807,"date_precision":"exact","month":9,"day":22},"death":{"year":1891,"d